{
  "doc_id": "49690",
  "text": "EpCAM has been long known as a tumor-associated antigen highly expressed in a variety of carcinomas [CITATION_1] . It is used as a marker for aggressive tumors, and has been considered as a potential target for immunotherapy [CITATION_2] . In human and mouse, EpCAM is expressed in embryonic epithelia, but the levels usually drop as cells reach terminal differentiation [CITATION_3] . Enhanced expression of EpCAM is associated with active proliferations of neoplastic or normal tissues [CITATION_4] . The protein can act as a homophilic Ca 2+ -independent cell-cell adhesion molecule [CITATION_5] . It is not structurally related to any of the major families of CAMs, but a potential link to the actin cytoskeleton via -actinin has been documented [CITATION_6] . Thus, it was initially proposed that enhanced proliferation and migration in cells expressing high levels of EpCAM resulted from sequestering -catenin away from E-cadherin [CITATION_7] . However, a recent study has shown that EpCAM is required to maintain the integrity and plasticity of the zebrafish developing epidermis where it works in partial redundancy with E-cadherin to promote cell-cell adhesion [CITATION_8] . Another study indicates that the enhancing effect of EpCAM on proliferation rates of carcinoma may in fact largely rely on a signaling activity of its intracellular domain [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] ). This short segment can be cleaved and is then able to form a complex with FHL2, -catenin, and Lef-1 that induces gene transcription of oncogenes such as C-myc and cyclins A/E. Thus, the role of EpCAM in cell-cell adhesion and the relative contributions of its potential adhesive and signaling activities in morphogenesis and proliferation remain unclear.",
